      <h2>Why Ashwagandha Gummies Are the Fastest-Growing Adaptogen in America</h2>

      <p>Ashwagandha (<em>Withania somnifera</em>) is a medicinal herb with over 3,000 years of documented use in Ayurvedic medicine. Known as "Indian ginseng" or "winter cherry," it belongs to a class of botanicals called adaptogens: compounds that help the body resist and recover from physical, chemical, and biological stressors. In the past five years, ashwagandha has gone from a niche supplement category to a mainstream wellness staple, with the U.S. market for ashwagandha supplements exceeding $270 million annually.</p>

      <p>The scientific basis for ashwagandha's stress-reducing properties is now substantial. A <strong>2019 systematic review published in <em>Medicine</em> analyzed five randomized controlled trials and found that KSM-66 ashwagandha reduced serum cortisol levels by 11-32% compared to placebo</strong>. Cortisol, the body's primary stress hormone, is directly linked to anxiety, weight gain, sleep disruption, and impaired immune function when chronically elevated. By modulating the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, ashwagandha helps restore hormonal balance without the sedating side effects of pharmaceutical anxiolytics.</p>

      <p>The gummy format has accelerated consumer adoption for one simple reason: compliance. Ashwagandha powder tastes bitter and astringent, and capsules require water and can be difficult for people who dislike swallowing pills. Gummies eliminate both barriers while delivering standardized extracts in precise, consistent doses. The critical consideration when choosing an ashwagandha gummy is the <strong>type and dose of extract</strong> — not all ashwagandha is equivalent.</p>

      <p>Three primary extract types dominate the ashwagandha supplement market:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>KSM-66</strong> — A full-spectrum root extract standardized to at least 5% withanolides. Manufactured by Ixoreal Biomed, KSM-66 has been the subject of 24 published clinical trials covering stress, cortisol, sleep, testosterone, muscle recovery, and cognitive function. It is the most widely studied ashwagandha extract in the world.</li>
        <li><strong>Sensoril</strong> — A dual-extraction from roots and leaves, standardized to 10% withanolides. Developed by Natreon Inc., Sensoril targets cortisol and cognitive function with a higher withanolide concentration per milligram. Fewer published trials than KSM-66, but the existing evidence is strong.</li>
        <li><strong>Generic root extract</strong> — Unbranded ashwagandha root or root powder without standardized withanolide content. Significantly cheaper than branded extracts, but potency varies between batches and manufacturers. Clinical outcomes are less predictable.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>We purchased all ten products in this guide at full retail price, tested each for a minimum of four weeks, and evaluated them against the clinical literature on PubMed. Below are our complete findings, ranked by overall quality, extract standardization, and value per serving.</p>
