    <section>
      <h2>Ashwagandha Extract Types: KSM-66 vs. Sensoril vs. Generic</h2>

      <div class="ing-box">
        <h3>KSM-66 — The Most Clinically Studied Extract</h3>
        <p>KSM-66 is a full-spectrum ashwagandha root extract produced by Ixoreal Biomed using a proprietary "Green Chemistry" extraction process that avoids alcohol and synthetic solvents. It is standardized to a minimum of 5% withanolides by HPLC, the bioactive compounds responsible for ashwagandha's adaptogenic effects. With over 24 published clinical trials, KSM-66 is the most extensively researched ashwagandha extract available. Key findings include: a 27.9% reduction in serum cortisol (2012, <em>Indian Journal of Psychological Medicine</em>), significant improvements in male reproductive health (2013, <em>Evidence-Based Complementary and Alternative Medicine</em>), enhanced cardiorespiratory endurance in athletes (2015, <em>Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</em>), and improved sleep quality scores (2019, <em>PLOS ONE</em>). The effective dose range across these studies is 300-600mg per day.</p>

        <h3>Sensoril — Higher Withanolide Concentration Per Milligram</h3>
        <p>Sensoril, manufactured by Natreon Inc., is extracted from both the roots and leaves of <em>Withania somnifera</em>. This dual-source extraction yields a higher withanolide concentration — standardized to a minimum of 10% withanolides, compared to KSM-66's 5%. This means that milligram-for-milligram, Sensoril delivers approximately twice the withanolide content. Clinical studies on Sensoril have demonstrated significant reductions in cortisol (up to 36% in one trial), improvements in sustained attention and reaction time, and reductions in C-reactive protein, an inflammatory biomarker. The effective dose range for Sensoril is 125-250mg per day, reflecting its higher concentration. Sensoril is particularly well-suited for consumers focused on cortisol reduction and cognitive function.</p>

        <h3>Generic Ashwagandha Root Extract — The Budget Option</h3>
        <p>Generic ashwagandha root extracts are unbranded products that do not follow the standardized extraction protocols of KSM-66 or Sensoril. They still contain withanolides, alkaloids, saponins, and other bioactive compounds, but the concentrations can vary significantly between manufacturers and production batches. Without standardized withanolide content (which may range from 1.5% to 5%), it is difficult to predict clinical outcomes with the same confidence as branded extracts. Generic extracts are the most affordable option and may be perfectly adequate for general wellness purposes, but they are not interchangeable with KSM-66 or Sensoril when citing specific clinical trial results.</p>

        <h3>Withanolides: The Active Compounds That Matter</h3>
        <p>Withanolides are a group of steroidal lactones unique to <em>Withania somnifera</em>. They are the primary bioactive compounds responsible for ashwagandha's adaptogenic, anti-inflammatory, and neuroprotective effects. Withanolides modulate the HPA axis by acting on cortisol receptors, enhance GABAergic signaling in the brain (producing anxiolytic effects), and exhibit antioxidant activity that protects neurons from oxidative stress. When evaluating an ashwagandha gummy, the withanolide percentage is the single most important quality indicator. A product with 600mg of 5% withanolide extract delivers 30mg of active withanolides, while 300mg of 10% Sensoril delivers the same 30mg — making them therapeutically comparable despite the different total milligram amounts.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

