    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Ashwagandha Gummies</h2>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What is the difference between KSM-66 and Sensoril ashwagandha?</summary>
        <p>KSM-66 is a full-spectrum root-only extract standardized to 5% withanolides, manufactured by Ixoreal Biomed with over 24 published clinical trials. Sensoril is a dual extract from roots and leaves, standardized to 10% withanolides, developed by Natreon Inc. KSM-66 has the broader clinical evidence base covering stress, sleep, testosterone, and athletic performance. Sensoril has fewer published trials but demonstrates strong cortisol reduction and cognitive benefits. Both are clinically effective — the choice depends on whether you prioritize breadth of evidence (KSM-66) or withanolide concentration per milligram (Sensoril). For most consumers, KSM-66 at 600mg or Sensoril at 300mg will produce comparable outcomes.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can I take ashwagandha gummies with other medications?</summary>
        <p>Ashwagandha has documented interactions with several medication classes. It may potentiate the effects of <strong>thyroid medications</strong> (levothyroxine) by increasing T3 and T4 levels, intensify the sedative effects of <strong>benzodiazepines and CNS depressants</strong>, lower blood sugar and amplify the effects of <strong>diabetes medications</strong>, and modulate immune function in ways that may interfere with <strong>immunosuppressant drugs</strong>. If you take any prescription medication, consult your healthcare provider or pharmacist before starting ashwagandha supplementation. This is particularly important for medications with narrow therapeutic windows.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>How long does ashwagandha take to work?</summary>
        <p>Based on published clinical trials, measurable changes in cortisol levels and stress perception typically appear within 4 to 8 weeks of daily supplementation at 300-600mg. Some users report subjective improvements in sleep quality within 1 to 2 weeks. The most cited timeline comes from a 2012 <em>Indian Journal of Psychological Medicine</em> study, which found significant cortisol reduction at the 60-day mark with 600mg KSM-66 daily. For best results, commit to at least 60 days of consistent daily use before evaluating effectiveness. Occasional or sporadic use will not produce the cumulative adaptogenic effects demonstrated in clinical research. For a detailed week-by-week timeline, read our guide on <a href="/blog/how-long-does-ashwagandha-take-to-work/">how long does ashwagandha take to work</a>.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What are the side effects of ashwagandha gummies?</summary>
        <p>At recommended doses (300-600mg/day of standardized extract), ashwagandha is generally well tolerated. The most commonly reported side effects in clinical trials include mild gastrointestinal discomfort (nausea, diarrhea, stomach upset), drowsiness, and headache. These effects are typically dose-dependent and resolve with continued use or dose reduction. Rare but serious adverse events include hepatotoxicity (liver injury), which has been reported in isolated case studies at high doses. Pregnant and breastfeeding women should avoid ashwagandha entirely. Discontinue use and consult a healthcare provider if you experience jaundice, dark urine, or persistent abdominal pain.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Does ashwagandha affect thyroid function?</summary>
        <p>Yes, and this interaction is clinically significant. Multiple studies have demonstrated that ashwagandha supplementation can increase levels of thyroid hormones T3 and T4. A 2018 study in the <em>Journal of Alternative and Complementary Medicine</em> found that 600mg of ashwagandha root extract daily for 8 weeks significantly elevated serum T3 and T4 levels in participants with subclinical hypothyroidism. While this is potentially beneficial for people with low thyroid function, it poses a risk for individuals with <strong>hyperthyroidism, Graves disease, or thyroid nodules</strong>. If you take thyroid medication (levothyroxine, methimazole), do not start ashwagandha without explicit clearance from your endocrinologist.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What is the optimal dose of ashwagandha per day?</summary>
        <p>Clinical research consistently supports <strong>300 to 600mg per day of a standardized ashwagandha extract</strong> for stress and cortisol management. Most studies demonstrating statistically significant cortisol reduction used 600mg of KSM-66 daily, while Sensoril studies showed efficacy at 125-250mg (reflecting its higher withanolide concentration). Doses below 300mg of a standard extract may not reach the clinical threshold for meaningful HPA axis modulation. Doses above 600mg have not consistently shown additional benefits in published trials and may increase the risk of gastrointestinal side effects. The effective daily dose of withanolides, regardless of extract type, appears to be approximately 20-30mg.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Should I take ashwagandha in the morning or at night?</summary>
        <p>The optimal timing depends on your primary goal. For <strong>stress and cortisol management</strong>, morning dosing (with breakfast) aligns with the body's natural cortisol awakening response (CAR), which peaks 30-45 minutes after waking. Modulating this morning cortisol surge can set a calmer baseline for the day. For <strong>sleep improvement</strong>, evening dosing (1-2 hours before bed) takes advantage of ashwagandha's GABAergic properties to promote relaxation and sleep onset. Some clinical studies split the dose — 300mg with breakfast and 300mg before bed — which covers both cortisol rhythm modulation and sleep support. This split-dose approach is our recommendation for most users seeking comprehensive benefits.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are ashwagandha gummies as effective as capsules or powder?</summary>
        <p>Yes, provided the gummy contains a clinically relevant dose of standardized extract. Ashwagandha withanolides are fat-soluble compounds with consistent bioavailability across delivery formats. The primary risk with gummies is <strong>underdosing</strong>: some brands reduce the active ingredient to accommodate the pectin base, sweeteners, and flavorings required for gummy production. Always verify that your gummy provides at least 300mg of a branded extract (KSM-66 or Sensoril) or 600mg of a generic root extract per serving. If the product meets these thresholds, the gummy format offers equal therapeutic potential with superior compliance — you are more likely to take a pleasant-tasting gummy every day than to mix bitter ashwagandha powder into water.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

